[0m[49m[39m  184, 185[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  185, 186[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  186, 187[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  187, 188[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  188, 189[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Runs Bayesian posterior updates; hosts simulation studies during design phase |
[0m[49m[39m  189, 190[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Stateless randomization service; returns arm assignments in <1 second |
[0m[49m[39m  190, 191[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores current allocation state and complete assignment audit log |
[0m[49m[39m  191, 192[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores outcome data, simulation results, and posterior history |
[0m[49m[39m  192, 193[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the posterior update pipeline with error handling |
[0m[49m[39m  193, 194[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | REST endpoint for site enrollment requests; authentication and throttling |
[0m[49m[39m  194, 195[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring, alerting on randomization failures or unusual patterns |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 195     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest (customer-managed keys for Part 11 auditability) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS WAF** | Rate limiting and IP allowlisting for the randomization API |
[0m[49m[39m  196, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  197, 199[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  198, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  199, 201[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  200, 202[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  201, 203[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Initialize trial parameters.** Before the trial starts, you define the prior distributions for each arm, the allocation constraints, and the update schedule. This configuration is the "protocol" for the adaptive system. It must be locked before the first patient is enrolled (protocol amendments require regulatory approval). The priors are typically uninformative (Beta(1,1) for binary outcomes, meaning "we know nothing"), but can incorporate historical data if justified. Minimum allocation constraints prevent any arm from dropping below a floor (typically 10-20%) to ensure sufficient data for inference.
[0m[49m[39m  202, 204[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 205[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  204, 206[0m:[39m[49m CONFIGURATION:
[0m[49m[39m  205, 207[0m:[39m[49m     trial_id          = "TRIAL-2026-001"
[0m[49m[39m  206, 208[0m:[39m[49m     arms              = ["Control", "Treatment_A", "Treatment_B"]
[0m[49m[39m  207, 209[0m:[39m[49m     endpoint_type     = "binary"           // response vs. no response
[0m[49m[39m  208, 210[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  209, 211[0m:[39m[49m     // Prior distributions: Beta(alpha, beta) for each arm
[0m[49m[39m  210, 212[0m:[39m[49m     // Beta(1,1) = uniform prior = "we have no prior information"
[0m[49m[39m  211, 213[0m:[39m[49m     priors = {
[0m[49m[39m  212, 214[0m:[39m[49m         "Control":     Beta(alpha=1, beta=1),
[0m[49m[39m  213, 215[0m:[39m[49m         "Treatment_A": Beta(alpha=1, beta=1),
[0m[49m[39m  214, 216[0m:[39m[49m         "Treatment_B": Beta(alpha=1, beta=1)
[0m[49m[39m  215, 217[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  216, 218[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  217, 219[0m:[39m[49m     // Allocation constraints
[0m[49m[39m  218, 220[0m:[39m[49m     min_allocation    = 0.10    // no arm drops below 10% allocation
[0m[49m[39m  219, 221[0m:[39m[49m     max_allocation    = 0.80    // no arm exceeds 80% (prevents premature convergence)
[0m[49m[39m  220, 222[0m:[39m[49m     burn_in_patients  = 30      // first 30 patients get equal randomization (10 per arm)
[0m[49m[39m  221, 223[0m:[39m[49m                                 // this ensures minimum data before adaptation begins
[0m[49m[39m  222, 224[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  223, 225[0m:[39m[49m     // Update schedule
[0m[49m[39m  224, 226[0m:[39m[49m     update_trigger    = "every 10 confirmed outcomes"  // or "weekly", depending on enrollment rate
[0m[49m[39m  225, 227[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  226, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 229[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Posterior update.** When new outcomes arrive, the system updates its beliefs about each arm's effectiveness. For binary outcomes with Beta priors, this is analytically simple: add successes to alpha, add failures to beta. The posterior is Beta(alpha + successes, beta + failures). This step runs as a batch job (SageMaker Processing) triggered by the Step Functions orchestrator whenever the update criteria are met. The output is a new set of posterior parameters stored in DynamoDB, immediately available to the randomization service.
[0m[49m[39m  228, 230[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  229, 231[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  230, 232[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION update_posteriors(trial_id):
[0m[49m[39m  231, 233[0m:[39m[49m     // Load current posterior state
[0m[49m[39m  232, 234[0m:[39m[49m     current_state = read from DynamoDB table "allocation-state" where key = trial_id
[0m[49m[39m  233, 235[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  234, 236[0m:[39m[49m     // Load new confirmed outcomes since last update
[0m[49m[39m  235, 237[0m:[39m[49m     new_outcomes = read from S3 "trial-outcomes/{trial_id}/confirmed/"
[0m[49m[39m  236, 238[0m:[39m[49m                    where timestamp > current_state.last_update
[0m[49m[39m  237, 239[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  238, 240[0m:[39m[49m     // Update posteriors for each arm
[0m[49m[39m  239, 241[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each arm in current_state.arms:
[0m[49m[39m  240, 242[0m:[39m[49m         // Count successes and failures in new data for this arm
[0m[49m[39m  241, 243[0m:[39m[49m         arm_outcomes = filter new_outcomes where assignment == arm
[0m[49m[39m  242, 244[0m:[39m[49m         new_successes = count(arm_outcomes where outcome == "response")
[0m[49m[39m  243, 245[0m:[39m[49m         new_failures  = count(arm_outcomes where outcome == "no_response")
[0m[49m[39m  244, 246[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  245, 247[0m:[39m[49m         // Bayesian update: conjugate Beta-Binomial
[0m[49m[39m  246, 248[0m:[39m[49m         // New posterior = Beta(alpha + successes, beta + failures)
[0m[49m[39m  247, 249[0m:[39m[49m         current_state.posteriors[arm].alpha += new_successes
[0m[49m[39m  248, 250[0m:[39m[49m         current_state.posteriors[arm].beta  += new_failures
[0m[49m[39m  249, 251[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  250, 252[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute new allocation probabilities using Thompson Sampling
[0m[49m[39m  251, 253[0m:[39m[49m     // Run many simulated draws to estimate allocation probabilities
[0m[49m[39m  252, 254[0m:[39m[49m     allocation_probs = compute_thompson_allocation(current_state.posteriors,
[0m[49m[39m  253, 255[0m:[39m[49m                                                     min_allocation,
[0m[49m[39m  254, 256[0m:[39m[49m                                                     max_allocation)
[0m[49m[39m  255, 257[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  256, 258[0m:[39m[49m     // Store updated state
[0m[49m[39m  257, 259[0m:[39m[49m     write to DynamoDB "allocation-state":
[0m[49m[39m  258, 260[0m:[39m[49m         trial_id         = trial_id
[0m[49m[39m  259, 261[0m:[39m[49m         posteriors       = current_state.posteriors
[0m[49m[39m  260, 262[0m:[39m[49m         allocation_probs = allocation_probs
[0m[49m[39m  261, 263[0m:[39m[49m         last_update      = current timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  262, 264[0m:[39m[49m         total_enrolled   = current_state.total_enrolled
[0m[49m[39m  263, 265[0m:[39m[49m         version          = current_state.version + 1   // optimistic locking
[0m[49m[39m  264, 266[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  265, 267[0m:[39m[49m     // Log the update for audit trail
[0m[49m[39m  266, 268[0m:[39m[49m     write to S3 "trial-outcomes/{trial_id}/posterior-history/{timestamp}.json":
[0m[49m[39m  267, 269[0m:[39m[49m         full state snapshot including posteriors, allocation probs, and input data counts
[0m[49m[39m  268, 270[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  269, 271[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN allocation_probs
[0m[49m[39m  270, 272[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  271, 273[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  272, 274[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Compute Thompson Sampling allocation.** This is the core RL logic. To determine allocation probabilities, we simulate many draws from each arm's posterior and count how often each arm "wins" (produces the highest sampled value). The winning frequency becomes the allocation probability, subject to the min/max constraints. This approach naturally balances exploration and exploitation: arms with uncertain posteriors (wide distributions) occasionally win and get explored; arms with well-characterized poor performance rarely win.
[0m[49m[39m  273, 275[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  274, 276[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  275, 277[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION compute_thompson_allocation(posteriors, min_alloc, max_alloc):
[0m[49m[39m  276, 278[0m:[39m[49m     num_simulations = 10000   // more simulations = more stable probabilities
[0m[49m[39m  277, 279[0m:[39m[49m     win_counts = initialize all arms to 0
[0m[49m[39m  278, 280[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  279, 281[0m:[39m[49m     FOR i = 1 to num_simulations:
[0m[49m[39m  280, 282[0m:[39m[49m         // Draw one sample from each arm's posterior
[0m[49m[39m  281, 283[0m:[39m[49m         samples = {}
[0m[49m[39m  282, 284[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each arm, params in posteriors:
[0m[49m[39m  283, 285[0m:[39m[49m             samples[arm] = random draw from Beta(params.alpha, params.beta)
[0m[49m[39m  284, 286[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  285, 287[0m:[39m[49m         // Which arm had the highest sampled value?
[0m[49m[39m  286, 288[0m:[39m[49m         winner = arm with maximum value in samples
[0m[49m[39m  287, 289[0m:[39m[49m         win_counts[winner] += 1
[0m[49m[39m  288, 290[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  289, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // Raw allocation = fraction of simulations each arm won
[0m[49m[39m  290, 292[0m:[39m[49m     raw_allocation = {}
[0m[49m[39m  291, 293[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each arm in posteriors:
[0m[49m[39m  292, 294[0m:[39m[49m         raw_allocation[arm] = win_counts[arm] / num_simulations
[0m[49m[39m  293, 295[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  294, 296[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply constraints: clip to [min_alloc, max_alloc] and renormalize
[0m[49m[39m  295, 297[0m:[39m[49m     constrained = apply_allocation_constraints(raw_allocation, min_alloc, max_alloc)
[0m[49m[39m  296, 298[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  297, 299[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN constrained
[0m[49m[39m  298, 300[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 301[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  300, 302[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION apply_allocation_constraints(raw_probs, min_alloc, max_alloc):
[0m[49m[39m  301, 303[0m:[39m[49m     // Clip each probability to the allowed range
[0m[49m[39m  302, 304[0m:[39m[49m     clipped = {}
[0m[49m[39m  303, 305[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each arm, prob in raw_probs:
[0m[49m[39m  304, 306[0m:[39m[49m         clipped[arm] = clip(prob, min_alloc, max_alloc)
[0m[49m[39m  305, 307[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  306, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // Renormalize so probabilities sum to 1.0
[0m[49m[39m  307, 309[0m:[39m[49m     total = sum of all values in clipped
[0m[49m[39m  308, 310[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each arm in clipped:
[0m[49m[39m  309, 311[0m:[39m[49m         clipped[arm] = clipped[arm] / total
[0m[49m[39m  310, 312[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  311, 313[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN clipped
[0m[49m[39m  312, 314[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  313, 315[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  314, 316[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Randomize a patient.** When a site enrolls a new patient, the randomization service reads the current allocation probabilities and performs a weighted random draw. The assignment, along with all inputs (allocation probabilities, random seed, timestamp, stratification factors), is logged to the audit table. This function must be fast (sub-second), highly available (sites can't wait), and perfectly auditable (every assignment must be reproducible given its inputs).
[0m[49m[39m  315, 317[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In production, the assignment write and enrollment counter increment must be atomic (use a DynamoDB transaction). A patient assignment without a corresponding counter increment creates an audit discrepancy that regulators will flag. The pseudocode below shows the logical steps; see the Python companion for the transactional implementation pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  316, 320[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  317, 321[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION randomize_patient(trial_id, patient_id, stratification_factors):
[0m[49m[39m  318, 322[0m:[39m[49m     // Read current allocation state
[0m[49m[39m  319, 323[0m:[39m[49m     state = read from DynamoDB "allocation-state" where key = trial_id
[0m[49m[39m  320, 324[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  321, 325[0m:[39m[49m     // Check if we're still in burn-in period (equal randomization)
[0m[49m[39m  322, 326[0m:[39m[49m     IF state.total_enrolled < burn_in_patients:
[0m[49m[39m  323, 327[0m:[39m[49m         allocation_probs = equal probability across all arms
[0m[49m[39m  324, 328[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  325, 329[0m:[39m[49m         allocation_probs = state.allocation_probs
[0m[49m[39m  326, 330[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  327, 331[0m:[39m[49m     // Generate assignment using weighted random draw
[0m[49m[39m  328, 332[0m:[39m[49m     // Use a cryptographically secure random number for regulatory compliance
[0m[49m[39m  329, 333[0m:[39m[49m     random_value = secure_random_float(0, 1)
[0m[49m[39m  330, 334[0m:[39m[49m     assigned_arm = weighted_choice(state.arms, allocation_probs, random_value)
[0m[49m[39m  331, 335[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  332, 336[0m:[39m[49m     // Log the complete assignment record (audit trail)
[0m[49m[39m  333, 337[0m:[39m[49m     assignment_record = {
[0m[49m[39m  334, 338[0m:[39m[49m         trial_id:              trial_id,
[0m[49m[39m  335, 339[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id:            patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  336, 340[0m:[39m[49m         assigned_arm:          assigned_arm,
[0m[49m[39m  337, 341[0m:[39m[49m         allocation_probs:      allocation_probs,       // what the probabilities were at assignment time
[0m[49m[39m  338, 342[0m:[39m[49m         random_value:          random_value,           // the random number used (for reproducibility)
[0m[49m[39m  339, 343[0m:[39m[49m         state_version:         state.version,          // which posterior version was active
[0m[49m[39m  340, 344[0m:[39m[49m         stratification:        stratification_factors,
[0m[49m[39m  341, 345[0m:[39m[49m         timestamp:             current UTC timestamp,
[0m[49m[39m  342, 346[0m:[39m[49m         total_enrolled_at_time: state.total_enrolled
[0m[49m[39m  343, 347[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  344, 348[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // IMPORTANT: These two writes must be atomic in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Use DynamoDB TransactWriteItems to write the assignment record
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // AND increment the enrollment counter in a single transaction.
[0m[49m[39m  345, 352[0m:[39m[49m     write to DynamoDB "assignment-audit": assignment_record
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 346     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 347     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Increment enrollment counter
[0m[49m[39m  348, 353[0m:[39m[49m     atomic increment state.total_enrolled in DynamoDB "allocation-state"
[0m[49m[39m  349, 354[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  350, 355[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN assigned_arm
[0m[49m[39m  351, 356[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  352, 357[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  353, 358[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Safety monitoring integration.** The DSMB (Data Safety Monitoring Board) operates independently of the adaptive algorithm. At pre-specified intervals, they review unblinded data and can override the system: pause enrollment, drop an arm for futility or safety, or stop the trial entirely. The system must support these overrides cleanly, without corrupting the allocation state.
[0m[49m[39m  354, 359[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DSMB override actions require a separate IAM role with explicit `dynamodb:PutItem` permission scoped to the allocation-state table, restricted to authorized DSMB statisticians. Consider requiring MFA or a step-up authentication mechanism for arm-dropping actions, as these are irreversible and affect patient safety.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  355, 362[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  356, 363[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION apply_dsmb_override(trial_id, override_type, parameters):
[0m[49m[39m  357, 364[0m:[39m[49m     // DSMB decisions override the algorithm
[0m[49m[39m  358, 365[0m:[39m[49m     // These are human decisions with regulatory authority
[0m[49m[39m  359, 366[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  360, 367[0m:[39m[49m     state = read from DynamoDB "allocation-state" where key = trial_id
[0m[49m[39m  361, 368[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  362, 369[0m:[39m[49m     IF override_type == "DROP_ARM":
[0m[49m[39m  363, 370[0m:[39m[49m         // Remove arm from active allocation
[0m[49m[39m  364, 371[0m:[39m[49m         // Remaining arms get its probability redistributed proportionally
[0m[49m[39m  365, 372[0m:[39m[49m         dropped_arm = parameters.arm
[0m[49m[39m  366, 373[0m:[39m[49m         removed_prob = state.allocation_probs[dropped_arm]
[0m[49m[39m  367, 374[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  368, 375[0m:[39m[49m         delete state.allocation_probs[dropped_arm]
[0m[49m[39m  369, 376[0m:[39m[49m         delete state.posteriors[dropped_arm]
[0m[49m[39m  370, 377[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  371, 378[0m:[39m[49m         // Redistribute to remaining arms proportionally
[0m[49m[39m  372, 379[0m:[39m[49m         remaining_total = sum of remaining allocation_probs
[0m[49m[39m  373, 380[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each arm in state.allocation_probs:
[0m[49m[39m  374, 381[0m:[39m[49m             state.allocation_probs[arm] = state.allocation_probs[arm] / remaining_total
[0m[49m[39m  375, 382[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  376, 383[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF override_type == "PAUSE_ENROLLMENT":
[0m[49m[39m  377, 384[0m:[39m[49m         state.enrollment_paused = true
[0m[49m[39m  378, 385[0m:[39m[49m         // Randomization service will reject new requests until resumed
[0m[49m[39m  379, 386[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  380, 387[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF override_type == "STOP_TRIAL":
[0m[49m[39m  381, 388[0m:[39m[49m         state.trial_stopped = true
[0m[49m[39m  382, 389[0m:[39m[49m         // No further randomizations possible
[0m[49m[39m  383, 390[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write with optimistic locking (same pattern as posterior updates)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // to prevent concurrent override and posterior update from conflicting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write updated state to DynamoDB "allocation-state"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         with ConditionExpression: version == state.version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         set version = state.version + 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  384, 397[0m:[39m[49m     // Log the override with full context
[0m[49m[39m  385, 398[0m:[39m[49m     write override record to DynamoDB "assignment-audit" with:
[0m[49m[39m  386, 399[0m:[39m[49m         type = "DSMB_OVERRIDE"
[0m[49m[39m  387, 400[0m:[39m[49m         details = override_type, parameters, timestamp, authorized_by
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 388     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 389     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     write updated state to DynamoDB "allocation-state"
[0m[49m[39m  390, 401[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  391, 402[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  392, 403[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter15.03-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  393, 404[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  394, 405[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  395, 406[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  396, 407[0m:[39m[49m **Sample allocation state after 100 patients enrolled (simulated trial with true response rates: Control=30%, Treatment_A=45%, Treatment_B=25%):**
[0m[49m[39m  397, 408[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  398, 409[0m:[39m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[39m  399, 410[0m:[39m[49m {
[0m[49m[39m  400, 411[0m:[39m[49m   "trial_id": "TRIAL-2026-001",
[0m[49m[39m  401, 412[0m:[39m[49m   "total_enrolled": 100,
[0m[49m[39m  402, 413[0m:[39m[49m   "posteriors": {
[0m[49m[39m  403, 414[0m:[39m[49m     "Control":     {"alpha": 13, "beta": 24, "mean": 0.35},
[0m[49m[39m  404, 415[0m:[39m[49m     "Treatment_A": {"alpha": 21, "beta": 22, "mean": 0.49},
[0m[49m[39m  405, 416[0m:[39m[49m     "Treatment_B": {"alpha": 7,  "beta": 23, "mean": 0.23}
[0m[49m[39m  406, 417[0m:[39m[49m   },
[0m[49m[39m  407, 418[0m:[39m[49m   "allocation_probs": {
[0m[49m[39m  408, 419[0m:[39m[49m     "Control":     0.18,
[0m[49m[39m  409, 420[0m:[39m[49m     "Treatment_A": 0.68,
[0m[49m[39m  410, 421[0m:[39m[49m     "Treatment_B": 0.14
[0m[49m[39m  411, 422[0m:[39m[49m   },
[0m[49m[39m  412, 423[0m:[39m[49m   "last_update": "2026-09-15T14:30:00Z",
[0m[49m[39m  413, 424[0m:[39m[49m   "version": 12
[0m[49m[39m  414, 425[0m:[39m[49m }
[0m[49m[39m  415, 426[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  416, 427[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  417, 428[0m:[39m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[39m  418, 429[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  419, 430[0m:[39m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[39m  420, 431[0m:[39m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[39m  421, 432[0m:[39m[49m | Randomization latency | 50-200ms (API Gateway + Lambda + DynamoDB read) |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 422     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | Posterior update time | 10-60 seconds (SageMaker Processing for simple models) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Posterior update time | 10-60 seconds compute + 3-5 minutes startup (SageMaker Processing cold start) |
[0m[49m[39m  423, 434[0m:[39m[49m | Allocation stability | Probabilities shift gradually; no sudden jumps after burn-in |
[0m[49m[39m  424, 435[0m:[39m[49m | Sample size savings | 10-30% fewer patients needed vs. fixed randomization (scenario-dependent) |
[0m[49m[39m  425, 436[0m:[39m[49m | Type I error | Controlled at 0.05 (verified through simulation during design phase) |
[0m[49m[39m  426, 437[0m:[39m[49m | Availability | 99.9%+ (Lambda + DynamoDB multi-AZ) |
[0m[49m[39m  427, 438[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  428, 439[0m:[39m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[39m  429, 440[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  430, 441[0m:[39m[49m - Trials with very delayed outcomes (6+ months to evaluate). The algorithm adapts slowly because it has few confirmed outcomes to learn from.
[0m[49m[39m  431, 442[0m:[39m[49m - Trials with many arms (5+). Thompson Sampling spreads allocation thinly and takes longer to identify winners.
[0m[49m[39m  432, 443[0m:[39m[49m - Non-binary endpoints (time-to-event, continuous). The Bayesian machinery gets more complex and computationally expensive.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 433     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - Multi-site trials with enrollment bursts. Many patients might be randomized between posterior updates, all using slightly stale probabilities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Multi-site trials with high concurrent enrollment. Multiple patients randomized between posterior updates all use the same allocation probabilities. Over many patients, the law of large numbers ensures correct aggregate allocation, but short-term deviations from target probabilities are possible. For trials requiring strict sequential randomization, add a DynamoDB conditional write with a sequence number to serialize assignments.
[0m[49m[39m  434, 445[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  435, 446[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  436, 447[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  437, 448[0m:[39m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[39m  438, 449[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  439, 450[0m:[39m[49m The math here is genuinely elegant. Thompson Sampling for clinical trials is one of those ideas that feels obviously right once you understand it. The implementation is not that hard either. A Beta-Binomial model with Thompson Sampling is maybe 50 lines of core logic.
[0m[49m[39m  440, 451[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  441, 452[0m:[39m[49m What's hard is everything around the algorithm:
[0m[49m[39m  442, 453[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  443, 454[0m:[39m[49m **The simulation studies take months.** Before you can run an adaptive trial, you need to simulate it under dozens of scenarios (different true effect sizes, different enrollment rates, different dropout patterns) and demonstrate that your Type I error is controlled and your power is adequate. This is a biostatistician's job, not a software engineer's, and it takes 3-6 months of careful work.
[0m[49m[39m  444, 455[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  445, 456[0m:[39m[49m **The regulatory package is substantial.** You're not just submitting a protocol. You're submitting the adaptation algorithm, the simulation results, the operating characteristics, and a justification for why adaptive randomization is appropriate for this specific trial. The FDA will review all of it.
[0m[49m[39m  446, 457[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  447, 458[0m:[39m[49m **Operational complexity is real.** Your EDC system needs to integrate with the randomization service. Outcome data needs to flow reliably and promptly. Sites need training on the adaptive design. The DSMB needs access to unblinded allocation data. The randomization service needs to be available 24/7 because sites enroll patients at all hours.
[0m[49m[39m  448, 459[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  449, 460[0m:[39m[49m **The sample size savings are often modest.** In the literature, you'll see claims of 20-40% sample size reduction. In practice, for well-powered trials with moderate effect sizes, the savings are often 10-20%. The ethical benefit (fewer patients on inferior arms) is real but harder to quantify in a regulatory submission.
[0m[49m[39m  450, 461[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  451, 462[0m:[39m[49m The part that surprised me: the biggest resistance isn't technical or regulatory. It's cultural. Investigators are trained on fixed randomization. Biostatisticians are comfortable with standard analyses. Introducing adaptive designs requires educating the entire trial team, and that education effort is often underestimated.
[0m[49m[39m  452, 463[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  453, 464[0m:[39m[49m Start with a trial where the ethical case is strong (rare disease, high unmet need, large expected effect size) and where the sponsor has experience with adaptive designs. Don't make your first adaptive trial a pivotal Phase III registration study.
[0m[49m[39m  454, 465[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  455, 466[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  456, 467[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  457, 468[0m:[39m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[39m  458, 469[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 459     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Platform trials with multiple experimental arms.** Instead of a fixed set of arms, new experimental treatments can enter the trial while others graduate (to Phase III) or are dropped (for futility). The I-SPY 2 model. This requires a more sophisticated allocation engine that handles arm entry/exit and maintains valid inference across the changing arm set. The architecture extends naturally: add arm management endpoints and modify the posterior engine to handle variable-length arm vectors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Platform trials with multiple experimental arms.** Instead of a fixed set of arms, new experimental treatments can enter the trial while others graduate (to Phase III) or are dropped (for futility). The I-SPY 2 model. This requires a smarter allocation engine that handles arms coming and going while keeping the statistics valid. The architecture extends naturally: add arm management endpoints and modify the posterior engine to handle variable-length arm vectors.
[0m[49m[39m  460, 471[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  461, 472[0m:[39m[49m **Bayesian predictive probability for early stopping.** Beyond allocation adaptation, compute the predictive probability that each arm will demonstrate superiority at the planned final analysis. If an arm's predictive probability drops below a futility threshold (e.g., <5% chance of winning at final analysis), recommend dropping it to the DSMB. This accelerates the trial by removing clearly inferior arms early.
[0m[49m[39m  462, 473[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  463, 474[0m:[39m[49m **Covariate-adjusted adaptive randomization.** Instead of a single allocation probability per arm, compute patient-specific allocation based on baseline covariates (biomarkers, disease severity, demographics). Patients predicted to respond better to Treatment A get higher allocation to Treatment A. This requires a more complex model (contextual bandits rather than simple bandits) but can further improve outcomes. Regulatory acceptance is less established for this approach.
[0m[49m[39m  464, 475[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  465, 476[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  466, 477[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  467, 478[0m:[39m[49m ## Related Recipes
